  'debt-snowball': {
    quickAnswer: 'The Debt Snowball method pays off debts from smallest balance to largest, regardless of interest rate. Each paid-off debt frees up money to attack the next one, creating momentum.',
    whatIs: 'The Debt Snowball Calculator organizes your debts from smallest to largest balance and shows a month-by-month payoff schedule. Popularized by Dave Ramsey, the snowball method works psychologically — quick wins from eliminating small debts build the motivation to tackle larger ones. While the avalanche method saves more interest, studies show the snowball\'s behavioral benefits lead more people to debt freedom.',
    howToUse: [
      'Enter each debt: balance, interest rate, and minimum payment.',
      'Enter any extra monthly amount you can apply to debt repayment.',
      'The calculator ranks debts smallest to largest and shows the payoff order.',
      'See total months to debt freedom and total interest paid.',
    ],
    formula: 'Pay minimums on all debts. Apply all extra money to the smallest balance first. When that debt is paid, roll its full payment to the next smallest. Repeat until all debts are cleared. The "snowball" grows as more minimums are freed up.',
    examples: [
      { title: 'Three Debts', scenario: 'Debt 1: $800 at 15%, min $25. Debt 2: $3,000 at 22%, min $60. Debt 3: $8,000 at 18%, min $120. Extra: $150/month.', result: 'Debt 1 paid in 5 months. Roll $175 to Debt 2 — paid in 11 more months. Roll $235 to Debt 3 — all debts clear in 30 months total.' },
      { title: 'Credit Card Trio', scenario: '$12,000 total debt across 3 cards, $200/month extra.', result: 'Debt freedom in approximately 26-30 months vs. 8+ years on minimum payments.' },
    ],
    useCases: [
      'Creating a motivating, structured debt payoff plan.',
      'Calculating debt freedom date from current balances.',
      'Financial coaching and debt management planning.',
      'Comparing snowball vs. avalanche for same debt portfolio.',
    ],
    faqs: [
      { q: 'What is the difference between debt snowball and avalanche?', a: 'Snowball: pay smallest balance first (most motivating). Avalanche: pay highest APR first (most mathematically efficient). Snowball costs more in interest; avalanche saves more money but requires longer patience before first payoff.' },
      { q: 'Does the debt snowball actually work?', a: 'Research from Harvard Business Review suggests that eliminating individual debts — regardless of size — boosts motivation and increases likelihood of staying on the payoff plan. The behavioral benefit often outweighs the mathematical difference.' },
      { q: 'What if two debts have the same balance?', a: 'Pay the one with the higher interest rate first since balances are equal. This acts as a tiebreaker that saves a small amount of interest.' },
      { q: 'How much extra money do I need to make the snowball effective?', a: 'Even $50-100/month extra accelerates dramatically. The more extra money applied, the faster the snowball builds momentum and the more interest is saved.' },
      { q: 'Can I use the snowball method with student loans?', a: 'Yes. List all loans from smallest to largest balance and apply extra payments to the smallest while paying minimums on others. For multiple federal loans, also consider income-driven repayment plans.' },
    ],
    aiQA: [
      { q: 'What is the debt snowball method?', a: 'A debt payoff strategy where you pay off debts from smallest to largest balance, rolling freed-up payments into larger debts.' },
      { q: 'Who invented the debt snowball?', a: 'The debt snowball method was popularized by personal finance expert Dave Ramsey.' },
      { q: 'Is debt snowball or avalanche better?', a: 'Mathematically, avalanche saves more interest. Behaviorally, snowball motivates more people to finish. Choose based on your personal motivation style.' },
      { q: 'How fast can I pay off debt with the snowball method?', a: 'It depends on your total debt and extra payment amount. Use this calculator to see your exact payoff timeline.' },
      { q: 'Does credit score improve with snowball method?', a: 'Yes. Paying off individual debts reduces utilization ratio and number of accounts with balances, both of which improve credit scores.' },
    ],
  },

