  'rule-of-72': {
    quickAnswer: 'The Rule of 72 estimates how many years it takes to double your money at a given return rate. Simply divide 72 by your annual return percentage.',
    whatIs: 'The Rule of 72 is a quick mental math shortcut for estimating how long it takes an investment to double in value at a given compound annual growth rate (CAGR). Divide 72 by the annual return rate to get an approximate doubling time in years. It works remarkably well for rates between 2% and 30% and is one of the most useful rules in personal finance.',
    howToUse: [
      'Enter your expected annual rate of return as a percentage.',
      'The calculator instantly shows estimated doubling time in years.',
      'Experiment with different rates to see how rate changes affect doubling time.',
      'Use the reverse to find the required rate to double money in a specific time.',
    ],
    formula: 'Doubling Time (years) = 72 / Annual Return %. Reverse: Required Rate = 72 / Desired Doubling Time. Example: 6% return: 72/6 = 12 years to double. 9% return: 72/9 = 8 years to double. At 1% (savings account): 72/1 = 72 years.',
    examples: [
      { title: 'Stock Market', scenario: 'Historical average S&P 500 return ~10% annually.', result: '72/10 = 7.2 years to double. $10,000 becomes $20,000 in 7.2 years, $40,000 in 14.4 years, $80,000 in 21.6 years.' },
      { title: 'Debt Cost', scenario: 'Credit card at 24% APR.', result: '72/24 = 3 years for debt to double if you make no payments. $5,000 becomes $10,000 in just 3 years.' },
    ],
    useCases: [
      'Quick mental math to compare investment options without a calculator.',
      'Teaching the power of compound growth and the cost of delay.',
      'Illustrating the devastating speed of high-interest debt compounding.',
      'Financial planning conversations about rate-of-return significance.',
    ],
    faqs: [
      { q: 'How accurate is the Rule of 72?', a: 'Very accurate for rates 2-30%. At exactly 8%, the actual doubling time is 9.006 years vs. 72/8 = 9. The error is under 1% for typical investment rates.' },
      { q: 'Why is it called the Rule of 72?', a: '72 is a useful constant because it is divisible by many common interest rates: 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 8, 9, 12, 18, 24, 36. This makes mental math easy. Some use 69.3 for greater precision at very low rates.' },
      { q: 'Can the Rule of 72 be applied to inflation?', a: 'Yes. At 3% inflation, purchasing power is cut in half in 72/3 = 24 years. At 7% inflation, it halves in just over 10 years. This shows why high inflation is so damaging to savings.' },
      { q: 'What is the Rule of 114 and 144?', a: 'The Rule of 114 estimates how long to triple money (divide 114 by rate). Rule of 144 estimates quadrupling time. All are based on the same compound interest math.' },
      { q: 'Is the Rule of 72 useful for retirement planning?', a: 'Yes. It quickly shows how many doublings occur in a working career. At 7% return and a 35-year career: 35/10 (years to double) = 3.5 doublings. $10,000 could become approximately $95,000.' },
    ],
    aiQA: [
      { q: 'What is the Rule of 72?', a: 'A shortcut to estimate doubling time: divide 72 by your annual return rate.' },
      { q: 'How long to double money at 7%?', a: '72 / 7 = approximately 10.3 years.' },
      { q: 'How long to double money at 10%?', a: '72 / 10 = 7.2 years.' },
      { q: 'What rate is needed to double money in 5 years?', a: '72 / 5 = 14.4% annual return required.' },
      { q: 'Does the Rule of 72 work for inflation?', a: 'Yes. At 3% inflation, purchasing power halves in 24 years (72/3).' },
    ],
  },

  'apr': {
    quickAnswer: 'APR (Annual Percentage Rate) is the true cost of borrowing, including the interest rate plus all fees, expressed as a yearly rate. APR is always higher than the stated interest rate.',
    whatIs: 'The APR Calculator computes the Annual Percentage Rate for a loan by incorporating both the nominal interest rate and any associated fees into a single comparable figure. Federal law requires lenders to disclose APR, making it the standard metric for comparing loan offers. A loan with a lower interest rate but high fees may have a higher APR than one with a higher rate and no fees.',
    howToUse: [
      'Enter the loan amount (principal).',
      'Enter the nominal annual interest rate.',
      'Enter any origination fees, points, or closing costs.',
      'Enter the loan term in months.',
      'Click Calculate to see the true APR including all costs.',
    ],
    formula: 'APR is calculated by finding the discount rate that makes the present value of all loan payments equal to the amount received (principal minus fees). For simple cases: APR ≈ Interest Rate + (Fees / Loan Amount / Years). Example: 6% rate + $3,000 fees on $100,000, 30 years ≈ 6.15% APR.',
    examples: [
      { title: 'Mortgage Comparison', scenario: 'Loan A: 6.5% rate, $2,000 fees. Loan B: 6.75% rate, $0 fees. Both $200,000, 30 years.', result: 'Loan A APR = 6.59%. Loan B APR = 6.75%. Loan A is cheaper if you keep it long-term.' },
      { title: 'Personal Loan', scenario: '$15,000 personal loan at 10% rate + $500 origination fee, 3 years.', result: 'APR = 11.2%. The fee adds 1.2 percentage points to the true cost.' },
    ],
    useCases: [
      'Comparing mortgage offers from different lenders.',
      'Understanding the true cost of a personal loan with fees.',
      'Auto loan comparison across dealers with different fee structures.',
      'Credit card comparison (APR is the key metric for cards).',
    ],
    faqs: [
      { q: 'What is the difference between APR and interest rate?', a: 'Interest rate is the cost of borrowing the principal. APR includes fees and costs, making it higher than the interest rate. APR is the more complete and legally required disclosure for loan comparisons.' },
      { q: 'Is a lower APR always better?', a: 'Generally yes — lower APR means lower total cost. But for very short-term loans, the monthly payment and payoff schedule may matter more than APR. Always read the full terms.' },
      { q: 'What is APR on a credit card?', a: 'Credit card APR is the annual interest rate applied to your balance if you carry a balance month-to-month. Unlike loans, credit cards typically compound daily. The average US credit card APR is 20-24% as of 2024.' },
      { q: 'What is a variable APR?', a: 'A variable APR changes with market interest rates, typically tied to the Prime Rate or SOFR. When the Fed raises rates, variable-rate loans and credit cards get more expensive.' },
      { q: 'What is the maximum legal APR in the US?', a: 'Varies by state and loan type. Payday loans can legally exceed 400% APR in some states. Most states have usury laws capping consumer loan APR. Federal credit unions cap personal loan APR at 18%.' },
    ],
    aiQA: [
      { q: 'What is APR?', a: 'Annual Percentage Rate — the yearly cost of borrowing including interest and fees, expressed as a percentage.' },
      { q: 'How is APR calculated?', a: 'APR reflects the interest rate plus all fees, annualized. It is higher than the nominal rate when fees exist.' },
      { q: 'Is APR the same as interest rate?', a: 'No. APR includes fees; interest rate is just the cost of borrowing the principal. APR is always >= the interest rate.' },
      { q: 'What is a good APR for a personal loan?', a: 'As of 2024, a competitive personal loan APR is 7-15% for good credit (700+). Average is around 12-20%.' },
      { q: 'What is a good APR for a credit card?', a: 'Below 15% is excellent. 15-20% is average. Above 25% is high and should be avoided or paid in full each month.' },
    ],
  },

